SIMPLE: snarl
RECORDS: 5

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Snarl
<hw>Snarl</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Snarled</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vvb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Snarling</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Etymol.
uncertain.]</ety> <def>To form raised work upon the outer surface of
(thin metal ware) by the repercussion of a snarling iron upon the inner
surface.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Snarl</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Snarl
<hw>Snarl</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[From <er>Snare</er>, <pos>v.
t.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To entangle; to complicate; to involve
in knots; <as>as, to <ex>snarl</ex> a skein of thread</as>.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧Her <xex>snarled</xex> hair.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To embarrass; to insnare.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>[The] question that they would have <qex>snarled</qex> him
with.</q> <rj><qau>Latimer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Snarl</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Snarl
<hw>Snarl</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A knot or complication of hair,
thread, or the like, difficult to disentangle; entanglement; hence,
intricate complication; embarrassing difficulty.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Snarl</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Snarl
<hw>Snarl</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <ety>[From <er>Snar</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To growl, as an angry or surly dog; to gnarl; to utter
grumbling sounds.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧An angry cur <xex>snarls</xex> while he
feeds.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Dryden & Lee.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To speak crossly; to talk in rude, surly
terms.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It is malicious and unmanly to <qex>snarl</qex> at the little
lapses of a pen, from which Virgil himself stands not exempted.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Snarl</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: Snarl
<hw>Snarl</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The act of snarling; a growl; a surly
or peevish expression; an angry contention.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Snarler</ent>⟦br⟧
